==Other versions of the legendarium==
In ''[[The Book of Lost Tales Part Two]]'', "[[Turambar and the Foalókë]]", the lame woodman who would come to love Níniel was called '''''Tamar Lamefoot'''''. He was the eldest son of the leader of the woodmen, [[Bethos]], and an Elf-maiden of the [[Noldoli]], making him [[Half-elven]]. Tamar, who was paid little attention to, grew to love Níniel, but in vain.<ref>{{LT2|II}}, p. 101</ref> It was Tamar who followed Níniel after the defeat of [[Glorund]], and who watched as Glorund revealed her identity to her. He continued after her when she fled, and saw her cast herself into the stream. Grieved, he returned to the people, and declared that Turambar was dead, and Níniel, who was in truth [[Nienóri]] the sister of Turambar, had cast herself into the stream and perished. But Turambar, who was not dead as had been thought, came back among the people. Upon hearing Tamar's proclamation that Níniel was Nienóri, Turambar thought him a liar, and slew him.<ref>{{LT2|II}}, pp. 109-111</ref>

In ''[[The Quenta]]'', Brandir's lameness was attributed to being wounded by an Orc-arrow as a child. He was also noted as uncomely and of less might than many; and for those reasons he yielded rule of the woodsfolk to Túrin by their choice.<ref>{{SM|Q13}}</ref>

